      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm working on my psych dissertation and i'm stuck on a weird result. my analysis shows a p-value of 0.06 for my main effect. some people are saying it looks like a trend, but my advisor is saying it's not statistically significant. can you explain the technical reason why 0.06 fails the standard threshold? also i'm struggling to differentiate between actual signal and just random noise in this context.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, being just slightly above the conventional $\\alpha = 0.05$ threshold, is indeed what makes your advisor's point sound right, though it's a tricky spot for many researchers. It's a classic case of the data not providing enough convincing evidence to reject the null hypothesis, which is the default assumption that there's no effect.\n\nThe technical reason it fails the standard threshold is purely statistical: the p-value represents the probability of observing your data (or more extreme data) *if the null hypothesis were actually true*. When $p=0.06$, it means there is a 6% chance you'd see this result just by random chance, and since most researchers set their threshold at 5% (0.05), you don't have enough statistical \"proof\" to declare the effect real.\n\nTo try and differentiate signal from noise, you need to look beyond just the p-value. Consider effect size, which tells you the *magnitude* of the difference, not just its existence. A tiny, barely perceptible difference might have a low p-value but be practically meaningless. A small effect size might be the difference",
      "source": "target",
